Narrative Log

Dev Log - 2026-05-11

Today was a contract day more than a feature day. The work centered on Command Center, but the real subject was not the interface itself. It was whether the shell behaved honestly under movement, scrolling, and state changes.

The first repair was the blank screen collapse. That work cleared away an overgrown page structure and left behind a smaller shell boundary that could actually be reasoned about. Once that was in place, the day shifted from “make it appear” to “make it behave.” That distinction mattered, because the next failures were not cosmetic. They were layout truths that did not survive contact with real use.

The rail-side bug was a good example. The UI said the rail could live on either side, but the actual layout only flipped the rail’s internal flex direction. That created visual jiggle without real positional change. Fixing it meant moving the preference up to the parent shell layout, where the side choice actually belongs. It is a small change structurally, but it removes a false signal from the interface.

The scroll fix was the same kind of correction. The page was allowed to scroll when the shell needed each lens to own its own motion. Once the containment chain was repaired, the interface stopped leaking scroll behavior outward. That is not glamorous work, but it matters because shell-level scroll leakage makes every downstream panel feel unstable. The system is easier to trust when each region contains its own movement.

In the same sweep, the shell’s visual hierarchy was sharpened. Workspace cards, the Agent Command header, stat summaries, and drawer tabs all got more deliberate surface treatment. This was not decorative polish for its own sake. It was about making the container legible enough that the user can tell what is primary, what is contained, and what is merely supporting context.

The other important thread was test coverage. The context directive and PI contract coverage were restored so the shell’s non-dispatch boundary is now defended by tests rather than memory. That matters because the shell’s job is not to execute work directly. It is to present work orders, preserve boundaries, and stay legible under failure. The tests make that boundary harder to erode later.

There was also a small migration-side alembic upgrade in the day’s work, but it sits beside the shell changes rather than defining the day. The dominant theme was still truth alignment: the UI now reflects its own control model more accurately, and the contract around what it may not do is better preserved.

What changed underneath the surface is simple to say and important to keep. Command Center is no longer just a rough layout that happens to render. It has begun to behave like a real shell with explicit boundaries, correct containment, and test-backed invariants. That makes the next round of work safer, because we are building on a surface that now tells the truth about itself.

The next useful step is to verify the repaired behavior in the running app, then separate out the unrelated RagTracePanel failures so they do not contaminate the shell story. After that, the same discipline can be applied to the remaining surfaces that still blur the line between presentation and contract.





